Faber retains the vulgar lection, but, nevertheless, admits that the manuscripts for vincendi exhibit ven- tarum, as proposed by Vossius, and for cursu, rursum. In Guernier, Marchetti, and all the other versions with which I arn acquainted, in which this triplet has been translated at all, currum has been understood li- terally for a land-chariat, and not metaphorically for a ship. This use of it, however, by Lucretius, is confirmed by the following verse of Catullus:

Ipsa levi fecit volitantem flamine currum. lxiv. 9.

To the light gale the flying car she bends.
